### Issue Description

Hello,

i have encountered a bug in the handling of the "read" field type policy.

The problem seems to be when:
 1. there is a read field type policy defined
 2. multiple (cache-wise matching) queries start fetching at the "same" time

They seem to corrupt their results by calling the read policy another time on a value that has already been processed by the policy.


### Link to Reproduction

https://github.com/FOODy/apollo-client-cache-typepolicy-read-multiple-call-bug

### Reproduction Steps

Run the example and take a look at the names in the person list.

After the person name should be only one "+", but because of the explained bug you will see "++".


Here are the relevant code snippets:

```tsx

const client = new ApolloClient({
  cache: new InMemoryCache({
    typePolicies: {
      Person: {
        fields: {
          name: {
            read: (existing) => existing != null ? existing + '+' : existing
          }
        },
      }
    }
  }),
  link,
});

```


```tsx
function App() {
// ....
  const { loading, data } = useQuery(ALL_PEOPLE);
  const _another = useQuery(ALL_PEOPLE); // <- Triggers another call on read
// ....
```



Wrong Result:

![image](https://github.com/apollographql/apollo-client/assets/151868/d1bc6014-082d-4d5d-bf23-aa96c5733793)


As i understand, the read policy should *not* modify the cache itself.

I'm working on an application and I'm using a complex strategy for state management. Therefore, I consider switching to apollo client as my state manager for its built-in caching mechanism.

I'm using codegen to generate hooks to interact with my graphql server, here is an example
```ts
const [createProductMutation, { data, loading, error }] = useCreateOneProductMutation({
    // options here
})
```

According to the documentation I can update the cache by providing the update function to my mutation call, and the hook that I generated also accepts the update method as an option..
```ts
const GET_TODOS = gql`
  query GetTodos {
    todos {
      id
    }
  }
`;

const [addTodo] = useMutation(ADD_TODO, {
    update(cache, { data: { addTodo } }) {
      cache.modify({
        fields: {
          todos(existingTodos = []) {
            const newTodoRef = cache.writeFragment({
              data: addTodo,
              fragment: gql`
                fragment NewTodo on Todo {
                  id
                  type
                }
              `
            });
            return [...existingTodos, newTodoRef];
          }
        }
      });
    }
  });
```

There is an update method in the hook generated by codegen, but according to the docs I have to pass in query/fragment I would like to update, but I am storing my queries in a seperate folder in .graphql files and in graphql language. Any ideas on how I can pass the query without copy pasting it into the update method of the hook everytime?

